<h2>HVAC Systems for Miami</h2>
<p>Miami's hot-humid climate demands high-efficiency HVAC systems capable of managing both temperature and humidity year-round. The optimal choice for Miami homes is a high-SEER central air conditioning system rated at minimum SEER 16, though SEER 18-20 systems provide superior performance and energy savings. Variable-speed air handlers paired with two-stage compressors excel in Miami's climate by maintaining consistent temperatures while effectively removing humidity, which is crucial for indoor air quality and comfort in this coastal environment.</p>

<p>For Miami's 1,680 square foot average homes, properly sized 2.5-3 ton systems typically provide adequate cooling capacity. However, proper sizing depends on factors including ceiling height, insulation quality, and window efficiency. Heat pumps offer year-round efficiency for the few mild days when heating is needed, while ductless mini-split systems work exceptionally well for Miami's many condominiums and homes with challenging ductwork layouts. Regular maintenance including coil cleaning and refrigerant checks is essential due to Miami's salt air and high humidity levels.</p>

<h2>Miami Energy Incentives</h2>
<p>Miami residents benefit from multiple solar incentives starting with the federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% credit on total solar installation costs through 2032. This credit applies to equipment, installation labor, and associated electrical work. Florida's solar-friendly policies include property tax exemptions for solar installations, meaning the added home value from solar panels won't increase property taxes, and sales tax exemptions on solar equipment purchases.</p>

